After some quick poking around I noticed that the `uv__async_make _pending()` code has optimizations for x86/64 and GCC, but a broken fallback case that went unnoticed:

```c
#if __i386__ || __x86_64__
  {
    unsigned int val = 1;
    __asm__ __volatile__("xchgl %0, %1" : "+r" (val) : "m" (*ptr));
    return val != 0;
  }
#elif __GNUC__ > 4 || __GNUC__ == 4 && __GNUC_MINOR__ >= 1 /* gcc >= 4.1 */
  return __sync_val_compare_and_swap(ptr, 0, 1) != 0;
#else
  *ptr = 1;
  return 1;
#endif
```

Essentially, `uv__async_always_make _pending()` always returns 1 in the fallback case, so that `uv_async_send()` *always* thinks there is a pending wake-up and never writes to the pipe to signal wake-up.

